[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Moriarty is a very pleasant 56-year-old male from Diamond Point New York.  He has a prior past medical history significant for morbid obesity, type-2 diabetes (with diabetic nephropathy and neuropathy in the lower extremities), hypertension and hyperlipidemia.  He has a baseline creatinine of 7.5 with a GFR of 15.
1.  August 2010 referred to the Sunrise Canyon Center for evaluation of possible kidney transplant.  CT imaging done (without contrast due to baseline kidney function) showed a thickening in the distal colon.
2.  August 30, 2010, underwent colonoscopy (first ever) identifying a sigmoid mass.  Biopsies confirmed adenocarcinoma.
3.  October 6, 2010, taken by Dr. Bellanger for a low-anterior resection.  Surgical pathology identifying a grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma invading through the muscularis propria into the pericolonic fat 4.4 x 4.3 x 0.9-cm in size.  Three of 13 lymph nodes positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma, negative surgical margins.  Staged at T3, N1b.
Mr. Moriarty is continuing to recover from surgery and is currently up ambulating during our consultation.  His overall kidney function has improved while hospitalized.  He has been followed by our colleagues in Nephrology who at this point have not recommended or initiated dialysis.  He is on the transplant list in Ansonville North Carolina.  He had no preoperative CEA.

